{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is most likely at the module handoff between request-builder and API client (payload assembly + dispatch wiring). A pure unit test of a helper can miss serialization/field-drop bugs in wiring. Rejected System/Agentic because behavior text is about request contents, not real network behavior or model judgment.","test_description":"Wire classifier module to a stub API transport that records outgoing payloads; assert every call includes the full configured taxonomy label list in the sent request body.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is local normalization/validation logic: given taxonomy + raw label, map out-of-set values to \"unknown\". No real infra or model variability is needed. Rejected Integration because the behavior can fail entirely inside one function boundary.","test_description":"Call normalization/classification-result handler directly with a mocked raw API label not present in taxonomy; assert output is exactly \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Determinism of normalization is a pure function property over fixed inputs. Multi-module wiring and real infra are not required to expose this failure mode. Rejected higher levels because behavior text explicitly scopes to \"normalization step\" with identical raw responses.","test_description":"Invoke normalization repeatedly with the same raw response fixture and taxonomy; assert identical final label across runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.93,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.0,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires repeated live AI API calls and consistency of returned labels; this depends on real model/provider behavior and potential non-determinism. A stub would hide real drift/variance. Rejected Workflow because this is repeated single-step classification, not a multi-step agent pipeline.","test_description":"Run N live classifications for the same document/taxonomy against the real provider, capture provider responses and final labels, and assert label stability when provider response content is unchanged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.17,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure boundary is between token-budget enforcement and dispatch control (must prevent over-budget request from being sent or apply truncation policy before send). Requires module wiring, but not real OS/network/model output. Rejected System/Agentic because behavior text is pre-dispatch enforcement logic.","test_description":"Use classifier wired to a fake dispatcher; feed an over-budget document and assert policy outcome (truncate or reject) occurs before dispatch, and dispatched payload (if any) is within computed budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This requires a real AI provider call and provider-reported usage metadata; mocks can trivially pass and hide real tokenizer/provider-side behavior changes. Although assertion is deterministic, execution depends on real AI API behavior. Rejected Workflow because only one model call path is under test.","test_description":"Execute live classification calls for representative documents and assert provider-reported token usage metadata is <= configured budget for each call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.23,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is retry-orchestration logic across classifier, backoff policy, and API client. A stubbed client returning rate-limit then success can expose real control-flow bugs. Rejected System because behavior text does not require real network timing/pathologies; rejected Agentic because correctness does not depend on model output quality.","test_description":"Wire classifier with a stub API that returns rate-limit error then success; assert module waits per policy, retries, and returns successful label instead of surfacing initial error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.09,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
